\begin_layout Subsection
Nuclear Levels as Signatures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nuclear structure of SNMs is a vital and important characteristic for
 detection of these materials.
 These materials all exhibit a large 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 cross section, where upon incident neutrons, the nucleus will be excited
 and emit a 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 These 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

s can be detected, and as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 detection and spectrometry is a well developed field, analysis can be done
 on these signatures.
 This is amplified in fissile materials in two ways, as the fission process
 multiplies source neutrons and emits 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

s.
 The following techniques leverage the nuclear levels and 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 cross section of SNMs to detect their presence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inelastic Scattering and Fast Fission Neutron Induced Reactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pulsed Fast Neutron Analysis (PFNA
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "PFNA"
description "- Pulsed Fast Neutron Analysis"

\end_inset

) was conceived by Gozani, Sawa, and Ryge in 1987 and has since been employed
 in many different capacities.
 The technique consists of a several step process.
 An incident beam of accelerated neutrons is collimated at the material
 in question.
 As an intermediate step, this beam of neutrons is chopped and bunch.
 Thus, a pulse beam of neutrons hits the material in a specific location.
 Upon interaction with the material, inelastic scattering causes a 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 release from the material.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 release is then detected by arrays of detectors (generally 
\begin_inset Formula $NaI$
\end_inset

).
 By analysis of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 energy and temporal profile, a spatial and temporal map of the materials
 in question can be deconstructed from this process.
 A diagram of this process is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:PFNA-Process-Diagram"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gozani2009a,Stevenson2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are physical limitations to the PFNA process.
 In general, the process is limited in that it
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
May only detect materials with large 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 cross section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
May be corrupted by scattering of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in materials - causing increase of voxel size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
May be eliminated by full attenuation of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 beam in materials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is adversely effected by finite time of flight of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 which causes disturbance of voxels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although these limitations are present, they have not deteriorated the impact
 of PFNA: it is still applicable and practical for many material sensing
 applications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gozani1995"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

