\begin_layout Standard
The practicality of PFNA comes from the coincidence of distinctive signatures
 with material that is dangerous to work with.
 Generally, each material will emit either quantized peaks of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

s or a continuous spectra of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 energies.
 The original use for PFNA was for the detection of explosives.
 This application benefited from the distinctive lines in the spectra of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 release from nitrogen (which is present in large quantities in all conventional
 explosives).
 Happily, though, there is an even more distinctive spectra available from
 SNM.
 Because of neutron multiplication within the material, an increased 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 cross section, and the emission of fission 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, an amplified and distinctive fission spectrum is detection when PFNA is
 used on SNM.
 In this way, PFNA easily transitions from use in detecting conventional
 explosives to SNM and is a viable technique for this application 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sawa1991,Gozani2009a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
X-ray Based Gamma Nuclear Resonance Fluorescence (NRF)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides having available 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 cross sections, many SNMs and materials of interest also have a large NRF
 cross section.
 NRF is the process of nuclear excitation by incident 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

s, and emission of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

s by decay 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Berttozi2007"

\end_inset

.
 This process will show very high amplitude peaks for SNM materials because
 the cross sections of these materials are in the several hundreds of barns.
 This process is described in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NRF-Process-Diagram"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The NRF technique has several large drawbacks.
 The process is a very high-Q system (the 
\begin_inset Formula $FWHM$
\end_inset

 of each peak is much smaller than the amplitude).
 Thus, an extremely high resolution detector is needed so as not to miss
 each characteristic peak.
 Usually Ge detectors are used.
 The process also has no inherent spatial resolution, so in order to create
 voxels, many tiled detectors must be used.
 Finally, the only practice source of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

s for this process is a very conversion efficiency Bremsstrahlung source,
 which must be driven at very high power 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gozani2009a"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

