\begin_layout Subsection
High Z Detection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 number of a material has a direct correlation to the attenuation coefficient
 of the material.
 The attenuation coefficient logarithmically affects the reduction in intensity
 of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 beam through the material, as given by the following correlation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I=I_{0}\exp\left(-(\frac{\mu}{\rho}\rho x)\right)\label{eq:Attenuation-Correlation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the incident intensity of the beam, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mu}{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is the mass attenuation coefficient of the material, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the density of the material, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the distance of beam travel through the material.
 The concept of high Z detection has been used for many years, in X-Ray
 interrogation, to investigate luggage and cargo.
 Several new techniques using this principle could extend it's usefulness
 to SNMs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dual Energy X-Ray
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplicity of the Dual Energy X-Ray technique is its main attractor.
 In this technique, two separate beams of X-Rays are focused on the material,
 one with higher energy than the other (generally used beams are 
\begin_inset Formula $6\, MV$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $9\, MV$
\end_inset

).
 Because of the higher attenuation coefficient at higher energies in high
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 materials, the intensity ratio of these beams can tell some information
 about the makeup of the material.
 This creates a mathematical relationship of the material and can be used
 to interrogate any material with significant differences in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 number of materials.
 This process is depicted in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Dual-Energy-X-Ray-Process-Diagram"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gozani2009a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Dual Energy X-Ray technique has many of the same physical limitations
 as the NRF technique.
 The sensitivity of the detector (this time resolution in intensity space,
 not in energy space) is required to be high.
 Also, the detector provides only one beam and thus a one dimensional map
 of the material.
 A sophisticated mobile system, or an array of systems must be used to create
 voxels for this process.
 This limitation has been somewhat ameliorated by the creation of digital
 fluorescent screens (as is used in medical X-Ray diagnosis) {cite!}.
 Finally, the integral equation created by the ratio of beam intensities
 through unknown material may only be solved by assuming binary systems
 (only high 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 or only low 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

) as well as other geometric assumptions.
 This technique is only applicable in specific instances 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chen2007"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

