\begin_layout Subsection
Overall Rating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The creation of an overall rating is not as straightforward as the compilation
 of the above material.
 The design process for a rating system is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Determine quantitative value for each of the above sections
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Bill of Materials - the complexity, cost, and common modes of failure will
 increase with each part in the BOM.
 Thus, the BOM factor will be determined solely off of the number of total
 parts in the BOM, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{BOM,i}=1-\frac{n_{i}}{n_{max}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the number of parts in the current technique, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{max}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum parts of any technique analyzed.
 More advanced weighting schemes could be developed, for instance the parts
 could be weighted on their cost, power consumption, probability of failure,
 or difficulty to use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Efficiency - an increase in the efficiency of the detector is desired, and
 this quantity is already normalized.
 Thus the value used to determine the efficiency factor is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{eff,i}\equiv\eta_{eff,i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{eff,i}$
\end_inset

 is the efficiency of the technique as calculated above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Spatial Resolution - the increase of the spatial resolution is desired,
 thus a normalized quantity directly proportional to the resolution should
 be used.
 This value will be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{res,i}\equiv\frac{res_{i}}{res_{max}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $res_{max}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum resolution of any technique given, and 
\begin_inset Formula $res_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the resolution of the current technique.
 The resolution of the current technique (
\begin_inset Formula $res_{i}$
\end_inset

) will be given by the number of voxels per square inch.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Added value - this will not be involved in the overall rating, as it will
 be implemented as a supplement for each system.
 As such, the added value section will not include any essential features.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Determine weighting scheme for each of the above sections - The weighting
 of these schemes is the most difficult and convoluted process.
 For different applications of these detectors, different weighting schemes
 would be important.
 For the application of a portal monitor, an adaptive weighting scheme will
 be used.
 The adaptive scheme is verbally defined as this: For techniques in which
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{BOM}<0.50$
\end_inset

, the efficiency and spatial resolution will be weighted as twice their
 nominal values.
 For techniques in which the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{BOM}\geq0.50$
\end_inset

, the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\equiv\lambda_{BOM}^{2}+\lambda_{eff}+\lambda_{res}$
\end_inset

 will be the overall factor.
 To explain this verbal definition, performance will excuse the increased
 cost and complexity, whereas for an elegant design, this is it's main selling
 point (although this effect should be mitigated by the performance).
 This is, admittedly, quite an arbitrary scheme.
 It would be possible to either interview portal monitor administrators,
 or to develop a neural network to weight the methods correctly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Determine additive or product scheme - The scheme must be additive, as the
 normalization of the above factors have determined the range to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\exists[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 If the scheme were product, certain overall factors would be trivial.
\end_layout

